	<h2>Option 1: Contractor Financing</h2>
	<p>Many fence companies partner with financing providers to offer payment plans directly:</p>

	<h3>How It Works</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Apply at time of estimate or contract signing</li>
		<li>Quick approval decisions (often same day)</li>
		<li>Payments begin after installation</li>
		<li>Terms typically 12-84 months</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Advantages</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Convenience:</strong> One-stop shopping for fence and financing</li>
		<li><strong>Promotional rates:</strong> Many offer 0% APR for 12-24 months</li>
		<li><strong>Simple application:</strong> Less paperwork than bank loans</li>
		<li><strong>Project-specific:</strong> Designed for home improvement</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Disadvantages</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Interest rates may be higher than banks after promotional period</li>
		<li>Deferred interest products can be costly if not paid in full</li>
		<li>May encourage overspending</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>What to Watch For</h3>
	<p><strong>Deferred interest vs. 0% APR:</strong> These are different. Deferred interest means if you don't pay the balance in full by the promotional period end, you owe ALL the interest from day one. True 0% APR means no interest accrues during the promotional period.</p>

	<h2>Option 2: Personal Loans</h2>
	<p>Unsecured personal loans from banks, credit unions, or online lenders:</p>

	<h3>How It Works</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Apply with any lender—not tied to contractor</li>
		<li>Receive funds, pay contractor directly</li>
		<li>Fixed monthly payments over set term</li>
		<li>Typical amounts: $1,000-$50,000</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Advantages</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Fixed rates and payments:</strong> Predictable budgeting</li>
		<li><strong>No collateral required:</strong> Your home isn't at risk</li>
		<li><strong>Competitive rates for good credit:</strong> Can be lower than contractor financing</li>
		<li><strong>Flexibility:</strong> Use with any contractor</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Disadvantages</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Rate depends heavily on credit score</li>
		<li>Origination fees may apply</li>
		<li>Takes longer to arrange than contractor financing</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Best Personal Loan Sources</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Credit unions:</strong> Often best rates for members (check local Stockton credit unions)</li>
		<li><strong>Online lenders:</strong> Quick applications, competitive rates (SoFi, LightStream, Marcus)</li>
		<li><strong>Traditional banks:</strong> Relationship discounts for existing customers</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Option 3: Home Equity Options</h2>

	<h3>HELOC (Home Equity Line of Credit)</h3>
	<p><strong>How it works:</strong> Borrow against your home equity as needed, pay interest only on what you use.</p>

	<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Lowest interest rates available</li>
		<li>Interest may be tax-deductible (consult tax advisor)</li>
		<li>Flexible—draw what you need</li>
		<li>Reusable credit line for future projects</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Your home is collateral</li>
		<li>Longer application process</li>
		<li>Variable rates may increase</li>
		<li>Closing costs may apply</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Home Equity Loan</h3>
	<p><strong>How it works:</strong> Lump-sum loan with fixed rate and payments.</p>

	<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Large projects where you know the exact cost and want payment stability.</p>

	<h3>Home Equity Requirements</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Typically need 15-20% equity minimum</li>
		<li>Good credit score (usually 620+)</li>
		<li>Proof of income</li>
		<li>Home appraisal may be required</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Option 4: Credit Cards</h2>

	<h3>When Credit Cards Make Sense</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Smaller fence projects ($3,000-$5,000)</li>
		<li>You have a 0% APR promotional offer</li>
		<li>You can pay off before interest kicks in</li>
		<li>You want rewards points/cashback</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Credit Card Strategies</h3>
	<p><strong>0% APR cards:</strong> Many cards offer 12-21 months at 0% for new purchases. If you can pay off within this window, it's free financing.</p>

	<p><strong>Rewards maximization:</strong> Earn cashback or points on a large purchase, then pay off immediately or transfer to 0% card.</p>

	<h3>Warnings</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>High interest rates after promotional period (typically 18-29%)</li>
		<li>Can damage credit utilization if balance is high relative to limit</li>
		<li>Easy to carry balance longer than planned</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Option 5: Paying Cash</h2>

	<h3>Advantages of Cash Payment</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>No interest costs</li>
		<li>May have negotiating leverage with contractor</li>
		<li>No debt or monthly payments</li>
		<li>Simple—no applications or approvals</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Cash Negotiation Tips</h3>
	<p>Some contractors offer cash discounts (typically 2-5%) because they:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Avoid credit card processing fees</li>
		<li>Receive immediate payment</li>
		<li>Have no financing paperwork</li>
	</ul>
	<p><strong>Note:</strong> Always get receipts and pay by check or bank transfer for documentation.</p>

